<subSubSection lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="11" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1436,1776,2002]" lastBlockId="10.[151,1436,152,378]" lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="11" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
Members of this genus were represented by one well defined species, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Straus)" baseAuthorityName="Straus" baseAuthorityYear="1820" box="[996,1315,1776,1802]" class="Branchiopoda" family="Moinidae" genus="Moina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="macrocopa">
<emphasis box="[996,1213,1776,1801]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Moina macrocopa</emphasis>
(Straus)
</taxonomicName>
, and by a group of three closely related genotypes in the 
<taxonomicName box="[735,917,1816,1841]" class="Branchiopoda" family="Moinidae" genus="Moina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="micrura">
<emphasis box="[735,917,1816,1841]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Moina micrura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group. According to the keys of 
<bibRefCitation author="Goulden" firstAuthor="Goulden" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" pagination="1 - 101" refId="ref9301" refString="Goulden, C. E. (1968) The systematics and evolution of the Moinidae. Transactions of the American Microscopical Society, 58, 1 - 101." type="journal article" year="1968">Goulden (1968)</bibRefCitation>
, all three phenotypes can be identified as 
<taxonomicName box="[716,848,1856,1881]" class="Branchiopoda" family="Moinidae" genus="Moina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="micrura">
<emphasis box="[716,848,1856,1881]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">M. micrura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but most cladocerologists agree that it is group of species. Evidence for this conclusion was given by 
<bibRefCitation author="Petrusek" box="[767,1027,1896,1922]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Petrusek" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" pagination="73 - 81" refId="ref10888" refString="Petrusek, A., Cerny M. &amp; Audenaert E. (2004) Large intercontinental differentiation of Moina micrura (Crustacea: Anomopoda): one less cosmopolitan cladoceran? Hydrobiologia, 526, 73 - 81." type="journal article" year="2004">
Petrusek 
<emphasis box="[877,938,1896,1921]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">et al.</emphasis>
(2004)
</bibRefCitation>
, who found reproductive isolation and deep divergence at 12S rRNA for populations of 
<taxonomicName box="[789,923,1936,1961]" class="Branchiopoda" family="Moinidae" genus="Moina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="micrura">
<emphasis box="[789,923,1936,1961]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">M. micrura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Europe and 
<collectingCountry box="[1143,1253,1936,1962]" name="Australia" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Australia</collectingCountry>
, suggesting the presence of two sibling species. In the case of Mexican material, the three subgroups separated by DNA barcodes show consistent morphological and distributional differences (
<figureCitation box="[971,1068,152,178]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,255,1245,1269]" captionTargetBox="[297,1291,198,1209]" captionTargetId="figure-290@4.[294,1292,197,1218]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1. 1.1 Sampling localities for all taxa; 1.2 Distribution of C. rigaudi complex: ⊕ C. cf. rigaudi 1, ∧ C. cf. rigaudi 2, ′ C. cf. rigaudi 3; 1.3 Distribution of C. cf. dubia; 1.4 Moina micrura group: M. cf. micrura 1, M. cf. micrura 2, ® M. cf. micrura 3; 1.5 Arctodiaptomus dorsalis: ℜ A. cf. dorsalis, ρA. dorsalis, A. cf. dorsalis 1 from Lachua Lake, ′ A. cf. dorsalis 2; 1.6 Mastigodiaptomus albuquerquensis: ♦M. albuquerquensis, ⊕ M. cf. albuquerquensis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5127616" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5127616/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Fig. 1.4</figureCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName box="[1091,1226,152,177]" class="Branchiopoda" family="Moinidae" genus="Moina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="micrura">
<emphasis box="[1091,1226,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">M. micrura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
1 is found in the semi-desert regions of the north, close to the Pacific side, while 
<taxonomicName box="[895,1028,192,217]" class="Branchiopoda" family="Moinidae" genus="Moina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="micrura">
<emphasis box="[895,1028,192,217]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">M. micrura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
2 seems restricted to the highlands of the Central Plateau at sites more than 
<quantity box="[624,713,232,258]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" unit="m" value="2000.0">2000 m</quantity>
above sea level. The third group, designated as 
<taxonomicName box="[1274,1406,232,257]" class="Branchiopoda" family="Moinidae" genus="Moina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="micrura">
<emphasis box="[1274,1406,232,257]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">M. micrura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
3, was found at a single northern locality, and shows an intermediate morphology to the other 
<specimenCount box="[1213,1329,272,298]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="generic" typeStatus="types">two types</specimenCount>
. It seems likely that none of these phenotypes are actually 
<taxonomicName box="[734,869,312,337]" class="Branchiopoda" family="Moinidae" genus="Moina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="micrura">
<emphasis box="[734,869,312,337]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">M. micrura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[878,943,312,338]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" sensu="stricto">s. str.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, described originally from 
<collectingCountry box="[1265,1351,312,338]" name="Austria" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Austria</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Kurz" firstAuthor="Kurz" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" pagination="7 - 88" refId="ref10232" refString="Kurz, W. (1874) Dodekas neuer Cladoceren nebst einer kurzen Uebersicht der Cladocerenfauna Buhmens. Sitzungsberichte der Akademie der Wissenschaften der ddr. Mathematik - Naturwissenschaften: Technik, 70, 7 - 88." type="journal article" year="1874">Kurz, 1874</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
